text: hey everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd this is a
review of the new oronzi pezuzu
album
these guys are a finnish rock band this
is their third full length lp i heard of
them back in 2010
thanks to their debut album which
actually dropped in 2009 but i was
actually kind of late on it but when i
actually got around to listening to the
album i was pretty excited by the band's
mix of black metal and other genres of
rock music because the music
on this album is actually quite spacey
to me their work on this lp is admirably
adventurous however their next album
really just kind of
breezed by me honestly there can be
moments when this band's riffs their
drumming just basically their songs in
general can come off a little static
still a little underwhelming on top of
that it's not like there aren't other
artists out there doing adventurous
things with black metal music at least
sonically
however in a way i will say that i feel
that oriancy sits at least on a throne
of their own because their approach to
this style of music at times just feels
outright trippy and certainly that vibe
leads through on this new record as well
for the six tracks and 47 minutes that
it lasts some of the songs on here are
the band's longest material yet 11
minute track on here 15 minute track on
here but the four average size songs
that surround these two monsters for
this band are pretty straightforward
like the opener vino verso where the
band delivers this pretty nice mid-paced
guitar riff got a good groove to it
[Music]
but this really only is a foundation on
top of which the band lays some very
twisted bright synthesizers some guitar
chords here and there that are so
distorted and brittle that they sear
like the sun and synth lines that are
constantly skipping in the background as
well however most of the experimental
characteristics of this song are really
buried in the mix behind the guitars
really thrown in the background placed
on the back burner while it's not a
horrible track and the riff does make
for an ear catching opener why add
adventurous or experimental elements if
they're not going to enhance the
experience of the song the fourth track
on here follows a similarly repetitive
formula but instead of a booming guitar
riff we have a very slow spacious bass
line and this bass line is a part of
what is essentially a very eerie
brooding and kind of psychedelic
instrumental i would actually call it
chilling if it weren't for the sort of
wobbly synthesizers playing through at
the end of the track making it kind of
feel like a corny halloween tape
soundtrack not every synthesizer part on
this track is a bust though for the most
part this is a pretty interesting
transitional moment on the album i think
my favorites of the mid-sized tracks on
this lp definitely have to be the second
track and the fifth track especially the
fifth track these songs are
multi-faceted and they stay pretty
engaging from beginning to end this
fifth song has a pretty nice guitar riff
that kicks things off some retch vocals
placed on top of this of course and then
the song gives way to some wailing
guitars on top of blast beats a very
intense combination and then it just
settles down into a rock groove that is
no less chilling and sort of reminds me
of something from the 28 days later
soundtrack this is the kind of
rollercoaster-esque songwriting that i
think made the band's first lp so great
and i wish they engaged with a little
more on here as far as the longer cuts
on this lp go there is or an insula
which starts off with a booming riff
that i think would be a fantastic start
for just about any metal track but then
the song begins to drag as it becomes
apparent that these awesome crushing
riffs have only become a music bed for
some decent vocals and guitar soloing
that is only interesting about half the
time the best parts of this track really
are the beginning and i think the last
four or five minutes of this song where
all of a sudden we have a huge explosion
of guitars and the band suddenly kicks
into this odd timed riff and even though
it is incredibly off-kilter they play it
in this really visceral way where the
groove is just so primal and fluid and
free and as far as the monstrous closer
on this lp goes not a bad track either
it's got a very quiet and eerie
guitar-led intro that reminds me of a
little bit of godspeed and then there's
an explosive riff that brings the song
to another plateau of intensity and even
though on this track like many other
songs here the the playing the
performance it's not
fantastically intense or mind-blowing i
do like the fact that this song
progresses in a much more interesting
way than other songs on here the band is
always looking for another level of
volume or another layer to add onto the
mix to sort of keep things engaging
there are times when synthesizers add
that and there's a moment toward the
very end of this track where there is a
very thick string section that is paired
really well with the thunderous guitars
that are clashing away behind it it's
just odd to me that a band would arrange
such a great piece of instrumentation
around their track and then just a
little bit earlier in the song like
around the 9 30 mark we have some guitar
intervals that don't feel all that well
mixed into the song and are simply going
plugging away in the background not
really adding that much to the song it's
just like there are moments where the
band is is adding another spice or
another ingredient another element to
the mix just to have something else
there or just to have an ornamental
little bit of sound there to separate
their tracks from what would normally be
just a straightforward black metal song
even though there are cons to this album
for me there are quite a bit of pros
it's recorded well the grooves are
really nice they get my head bobbing the
mix is great there's a variety among the
tracks the album for sure
flows well and for sure orienty sits at
an interesting crossroads of different
genres but there are moments here where
some of the guitar riffs or the soloing
the sound play feels a little
average and that goes for black metal
metal psychedelic rock whatever genre
you feel like really sticks out at you
when it comes to this record i'm feeling
a strong six to a light seven on this
thing position but if you've given this
lp a listen what did you think of it did
you love it hate it why
